<section id="book">
  <p class="section-label">From Myth to Meme</p>
  <h2 class="section-headline">Why stories rule us</h2>

  <div class="book-frame">
    <div class="book-prose">
      <p class="opener">You are living inside a story. So is everyone you have ever met.</p>

      <p>For most of human history, narrative was how we stayed alive. The first human technology. The soft, slow, badly-equipped species, with the neat trick of getting what was in one head into all the heads, and across time into heads that hadn&rsquo;t been born yet.</p>

      <p>Two-thirds of human conversation is still doing it, and there is no civilisation, no movement, no brand, no version of yourself that wasn&rsquo;t built on it.</p>

      <p>So, what do Captain Caveman, Han Solo, and a dead Roman Legionary travelling to unknown lands have in common? As it turns out, me. And who I&rsquo;ve become.</p>

      <p>From the stories that got into you before you knew what was happening. The team, the song, the universe you&rsquo;d have lived in if you could. The Jedi, the hobbit, the prophet, the parent. The characters who walked into your head and rearranged the furniture. The things you loved before you had language for why, and the things that got you through.</p>

      <p>This is a book about how that happened, what it means, and what becomes possible once you can see it.</p>

      <p>It won&rsquo;t tell you to stop believing in stories. That would be like telling you to stop breathing. It will give you the view from far enough away that the familiar goes strange. And once you&rsquo;ve seen it, the stories only get richer, and you can begin to more intentionally write your own.</p>

      <p>Know you&rsquo;re in a story. Pick the right ones. And believe in them consciously.</p>

      <p>Because just maybe, that&rsquo;s the bravest possible response to understanding how our weird yet wonderful world actually works. And the most honest place to start writing the next chapter.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
